This question already has answers here : Finding the limit of $\frac {n}{\sqrt[n]{n!}}$ (11 answers) Closed 3 years ago . Calculate the value of the limit $$
\lim_{n\rightarrow \infty}\left(\frac{n!}{n^n}\right)^{1/n}
$$ Can we solve this without using a Riemann sum method? If so, how?

Long time ago I've been playng with formulas for $\pi$ and found that one above in the title which can also be expressed as 
\begin{align*}
\;\pi=\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\left(\frac{2^{4k+1}+1}{(8k+1)}+\frac{2^{4k+2}-1}{(8k+3)2^{2}}-\frac{2^{4k+3}-1}{(8k+5)2^{4}}-\frac{2^{4k+4}+1}{(8k+7)2^{6}} \right )\frac{1}{2^{8k}}
\end{align*} Unfortunately I can't find in my notes how I derived it. I remember that I used some trick. I've seen similar formulas on Wikipedia but not this one. Does anyone knows how to derive this kind of formulas? Thanks. Just for clarification : The formula in the title is just a shortened version because the second one was bigger than 150 chars and the system didn't accept it, but I prefer the second. I think its more elegant. So I'm looking for a way to derive any of the two.

The following equation provides the inclination ($i$) of a galaxy, using the ratio of its two axes: $$
\cos^2 i = {(b/a)^2 − (b/a)^2_{eos} \over 1 − (b/a)^2_{eos}}
$$ All I need however is to determine the value of $i$. Can someone walk me through solving this for both a normal $\cos\theta$ (using $\arccos\theta$ I assume), and then $\cos^2\theta$? Update Taking the basic trig provided by DonAntonio, I get this: $$
\frac{\cos 2i+1}{2} = {(b/a)^2 − (b/a)^2_{eos} \over 1 − (b/a)^2_{eos}}
$$ Then ... (poorly formatted I know) ...
$$
i = \frac{\arccos\Bigg(\bigg(2\big({(b/a)^2 − (b/a)^2_{eos} \over 1 − (b/a)^2_{eos}}\big)\bigg)-1\Bigg)}{2}
$$ Thanks.
